        SINGAPORE THE SUNDAY TIMES A17 SUNDAY, NOVEMBER 22, 2020 | | | • • • • Artist’s impression of the Park Connector within Lornie Nature Corridor with more mature vegetation. • • • • Source: NPARKS IMAGES: NPARKS, ZAKI JAMIL, LEE JIA HWA, ANG WEE FOONG, VICK Y LIM YEN NGOH, CHUA LIAT SENG GARY, PAULINE TAY SUNDAY TIMES GRAPHICS PRINTED AND DISTRIBUTE­D BY PRESSREADE­R PressReade­r.com +1 604 278 4604 ORIGINAL COPY . ORIGINAL COPY . ORIGINAL COPY . ORIGINAL COPY . ORIGINAL COPY . ORIGINAL COPY COPYRIGHT AND PROTECTED BY APPLICABLE LAW Jelutong (Dyera costulata) REWILDING PLANS: A process where plants are allowed to grow naturally with selective interventi­on.
A curated planting palette that includes native trees, shrubs, wildflower­s, as well as some common and naturalise­d wildflower­s.
The plan is being rolled out progressiv­ely at 32 stretches of nature ways, roads and parks over the next three years.
Upcoming rewilding sites: Ang Mo Kio Ave 1, Kheam Hock Road, Old Choa Chu Kang Road, and Upper Thomson Road, Bedok Reservoir Park and Bishan-Ang Mo Kio Park. (Koompassia malaccensi­s) Mempat (Cratoxylum formosum) Kempas (Bidens pilosa) Comprises a nature way and a park connector. Abuts the Central Catchment Nature Reserve. • Lornie Road has been converted to a dual 2-lane road; part of the original road was reclaimed for greenery and recreation. • • LORNIE NATURE CORRIDOR • More than 100 species of trees and shrubs were planted to mimic a rainforest . Beggar’s Tick Common Asystasia (Asystasia gangetica subsp. micrantha) Red Leea (Leea rubra) Additional­ly, as part of NParks’ One Million Trees movement, a further 150 trees were planted together with the community yesterday. Common Sendudok (Melastoma malabathri­cum) Rose Myrtle (Rhodomyrtu­s tomentosa) Singaporea­ns can now step into the green surroundin­gs of the newly opened Lornie Nature Corridor situated along Lornie Road.
Clara Chong looks at some of the efforts taken by the National Parks Board to restore nature in the urban landscape along this 1.76km stretch of space. The Lornie Nature Corridor is part of a 10km rewilding stretch that starts from Kheam Hock Road, connects to Lornie Road, and then Upper Thomson Road.
This corridor links major green spaces: the Central Catchment Nature Reserve, Singapore Botanic Gardens, Lornie Nature Corridor and Kheam Hock Nature Way along Kheam Hock Road.
The park connector within Lornie Nature Corridor is part of the Coast-to-Coast Trail and provides recreation­al opportunit­ies amid nature. Upcoming Upper Thomson Nature Way along
